<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-435-876  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 435 876.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computing Canada  June 22 1989 v15 n13 p27(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Automation: a matter of control.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Rickards, Jim.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The uniqueness of every data processing center demands asystematic analysis of the automation needs of each of them.andP;  Anyautomation project must, if it is to be successful, address thedata processing department as a complete and integratedenvironment.andP;  The selection of new automation tools must beinfluenced by a consideration of how they will operate within thepresent system.andP;  An automation project can be tailored to anindividual data center by following the four basic steps: theestablishment of a central repository and data base, theautomation of batch and on-line production, the automation ofconsole management and lastly the automation of networkenvironment.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     AutomationData ProcessingMISManagementGuidelines.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>